body:
I'm seeing a constant folding bug in a large SoC project (OpenTitan). Annoyingly, I can only reproduce this with the large top-level: building just the relevant block doesn't trigger it. To reproduce with the whole system:

- `git clone -b veribug https://github.com/rswarbrick/opentitan.git`
- Build the top-level system with Verilator (using fusesoc):
   ```
  fusesoc --cores-root=. \
    run --flag=fileset_top --target=sim --setup --build \
    --build-root="build/hw" \
    lowrisc:systems:top_earlgrey_verilator
   ```
- Either run the result or (easier) look at the generated C++ (see below).

I've bisected the problem down to commit bb5384b, which makes sense because it's a constant folding change.

The code that is being mis-compiled is in `pwrmgr_slow_fsm.sv`. There, line 144 has the following item of a `case` statement:
```systemverilog
      SlowPwrStateReqPwrUp: begin
        req_pwrup_d = 1'b1;

        // req_pwrdn_i should be 0 here to indicate
        // the request from the previous round has definitely completed
        if (ack_pwrup_i && !req_pwrdn_i) begin
          req_pwrup_d = 1'b0;
          state_d = SlowPwrStateIdle;
        end
      end
```

In the full system, this gets compiled by verilator v4.110 to the following sequent (this is from `build/hw/sim-verilator/Vtop_earlgrey_verilator__49.cpp`). Note that there's nothing setting `req_pwrup_d` to zero again.
```c++
    vlTOPp->top_earlgrey_verilator__DOT__top_earlgrey__DOT__u_pwrmgr_aon__DOT__i_slow_fsm__DOT__req_pwrup_d 
        = vlTOPp->top_earlgrey_verilator__DOT__top_earlgrey__DOT__u_pwrmgr_aon__DOT__i_slow_fsm__DOT__req_pwrup_q;
    if ((1U & (~ ((IData)(vlTOPp->top_earlgrey_verilator__DOT__top_earlgrey__DOT__u_pwrmgr_aon__DOT__i_slow_fsm__DOT__state_q) 
                  >> 3U)))) {
        if ((4U & (IData)(vlTOPp->top_earlgrey_verilator__DOT__top_earlgrey__DOT__u_pwrmgr_aon__DOT__i_slow_fsm__DOT__state_q))) {
            if ((1U & (~ ((IData)(vlTOPp->top_earlgrey_verilator__DOT__top_earlgrey__DOT__u_pwrmgr_aon__DOT__i_slow_fsm__DOT__state_q) 
                          >> 1U)))) {
                if ((1U & (~ (IData)(vlTOPp->top_earlgrey_verilator__DOT__top_earlgrey__DOT__u_pwrmgr_aon__DOT__i_slow_fsm__DOT__state_q)))) {
                    vlTOPp->top_earlgrey_verilator__DOT__top_earlgrey__DOT__u_pwrmgr_aon__DOT__i_slow_fsm__DOT__req_pwrup_d = 1U;
                }
            }
        }
    }
```

By comparison, version v4.108 generates the following. (This is from build/hw/sim-verilator/Vtop_earlgrey_verilator__50.cpp)
```c++
    vlTOPp->top_earlgrey_verilator__DOT__top_earlgrey__DOT__u_pwrmgr_aon__DOT__i_slow_fsm__DOT__req_pwrup_d 
        = vlTOPp->top_earlgrey_verilator__DOT__top_earlgrey__DOT__u_pwrmgr_aon__DOT__i_slow_fsm__DOT__req_pwrup_q;
    if ((1U & (~ ((IData)(vlTOPp->top_earlgrey_verilator__DOT__top_earlgrey__DOT__u_pwrmgr_aon__DOT__i_slow_fsm__DOT__state_q) 
                  >> 3U)))) {
        if ((4U & (IData)(vlTOPp->top_earlgrey_verilator__DOT__top_earlgrey__DOT__u_pwrmgr_aon__DOT__i_slow_fsm__DOT__state_q))) {
            if ((1U & (~ ((IData)(vlTOPp->top_earlgrey_verilator__DOT__top_earlgrey__DOT__u_pwrmgr_aon__DOT__i_slow_fsm__DOT__state_q) 
                          >> 1U)))) {
                if ((1U & (~ (IData)(vlTOPp->top_earlgrey_verilator__DOT__top_earlgrey__DOT__u_pwrmgr_aon__DOT__i_slow_fsm__DOT__state_q)))) {
                    vlTOPp->top_earlgrey_verilator__DOT__top_earlgrey__DOT__u_pwrmgr_aon__DOT__i_slow_fsm__DOT__req_pwrup_d = 1U;
                    if (((IData)(vlSymsp->TOP__top_earlgrey_verilator__DOT__top_earlgrey__DOT__u_pwrmgr_aon__DOT__i_cdc__DOT__i_ack_pwrup_sync.q_o) 
                         & (~ (IData)(vlSymsp->TOP__top_earlgrey_verilator__DOT__top_earlgrey__DOT__u_pwrmgr_aon__DOT__i_cdc__DOT__i_req_pwrdn_sync.q_o)))) {
                        vlTOPp->top_earlgrey_verilator__DOT__top_earlgrey__DOT__u_pwrmgr_aon__DOT__i_slow_fsm__DOT__req_pwrup_d = 0U;
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }
```

The obvious question is whether this is just an example of Verilator's constant folding getting better. But that doesn't seem to be the case: this screenshot shows wave dumps from an example run with v4.110:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/104845/110627502-f7a99e80-8199-11eb-9ba6-3717f5c4c247.png)

Note that `ack_pwrup_i && !req_pwrdn_i` is true, but `req_pwrup_d` isn't getting cleared (as you'd expect, since the `if` statement was folded away).

If this isn't enough information to track down what's going on, I can try to cut down the example but this will take me a few weeks to get to because of some deadlines at work. Hopefully this is already enough to figure out what's come unstuck.
